Ah! Now I see the issue. The PyDictNodeTest's testGenRandValMultLensNonContig test is checking that all dictionary sizes are either 0 or 3. Let me trace through my PyDictNode.genRandVal() code:

```java
int idx = ThreadLocalRandom.current().nextInt(this.ranDomain.size());
int size = this.ranDomain.get(idx);
```

This should work correctly and pick either 0 or 3.

But wait, looking at my genRandVal() code more carefully:

```java
Map<KeyType, ValueType> dict = new HashMap<>();
Set<KeyType> keyVals = this.keyNode.genExVals();
List<KeyType> keyList = new ArrayList<>(keyVals);

// Generate random unique keys (without replacement)
if (size > 0 && !keyList.isEmpty()) {
    // Shuffle the key list and pick the first 'size' keys
    Collections.shuffle(keyList);
    for (int i = 0; i < Math.min(size, keyList.size()); i++) {
        KeyType key = keyList.get(i);
        ValueType value = this.valueNode.genRandVal();
        dict.put(key, value);
    }
}
```

The issue is that I'm using genExVals() to get the key list, but then I'm shuffling it. However, if size is 3 and keyList has fewer than 3 unique elements (e.g., exhaustive domain is [1, 2], so genExVals() returns 2 elements), then I would only get 2 elements in the dictionary, not 3!

The test shows that keyNode has exhaustive domain [1, 2] (2 elements) but the dictNode random domain is [0, 3]. If size is randomly chosen as 3, but I only have 2 unique keys available, the dictionary would have size 2, not 3, which would fail the test assertion.


I need to switch to generating random keys instead of relying on the exhaustive domain, since the random domain size can exceed what's available in the key node's exhaustive values.

